      "date": "2022-03-05 00:07:57.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nBuild Failed \n\nhttps://build.whamcloud.com/job/lustre-reviews/86508/ : FAILURE",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "dbb2c7e91382dd832ce7a70b9be92f0bebd6c4bf",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2022-03-05 00:07:58.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1\n\nI don't think we can have a binary blob installed, as this will fail on aarch64 and ppc64, and will consume a bunch of space in Git.  I had incorrectly assumed that shellcheck would itself be It should just run the installed shellcheck command if it is available.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "59752c363e4350756e784fd5419876d5a2a1e078",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 655,
        "name": "Arshad Hussain",
        "email": "arshad.hussain@aeoncomputing.com",
        "username": "arshad512"
      },
      "date": "2022-03-05 00:14:30.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\n>I don't think we can have a binary blob installed, as this will fail on aarch64 and ppc64...\n\nAgree. I just check on my yum sourced shellcheck and it did not have \"-S \" as an option. Sorry about this. I will remove the shellcheck binary.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "f4fb96d1e768dee85972e46a1acbd7ae7f6e46d9",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2022-03-05 00:19:20.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nIt may also be necessary to fix at least the error cases before landing this to avoid spurious errors unrelated to the patches.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "c268394524ed5ae2e1c3b46de996ef509fcbc6d9",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2022-03-05 00:29:15.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\n(1 comment)",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "b1676b22090b72d974eaa93f8e12de81a92d06e9",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2022-03-05 00:36:50.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\none question - does this only run shellcheck on the part of the script that is within the patch context, or does it run on the whole script file?  I'd think the former would be very hard to implement, but would be preferable, while the latter is bound to produce false positives if there are unfixed errors in the script.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "65cf57d71c174ce3db3aa550a31a63358b59c62f",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 655,
        "name": "Arshad Hussain",
        "email": "arshad.hussain@aeoncomputing.com",
        "username": "arshad512"
      },
      "date": "2022-03-05 00:55:07.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\n>one question - does this only run shellcheck on the part of the script that is within the patch context, or does it run on the whole script file? ...\n\nAndreas, this version runs on the whole file. Not the patch context. \n\n>... I'd think the former would be very hard to implement, but would be preferable, while the latter is bound to produce false positives if there are unfixed errors in the script.\n\nI do not think shellcheck can run of patched diff. I will check that out. What we can do is to carefully limit shellcheck to only throw or parse specific errors not all. True, if we run shellcheck run as-is, there are tons of false positives.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "7a760e2d853e0fd279c9814dfa2252733770a6d7",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2022-03-05 02:07:30.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nIt looks like the number of \"error:\" lines for most scripts are manageable, though there are a few spurious ones that should be fixed before this lands (e.g. double quotes around \"$@\" and such).\n\nEnabling \"warning:\" lines would be more tricky since there are many more.  One option would potentially be post-processing the full-file shellcheck output, limiting it to lines that are within the context of the patch.  Something like:\n\n    range=($(git show <file> | awk /^@@/ { print $3 } |\n             sed -e 's/+//' -e 's/,/ /'))\n    start=${range[0]}\n    end=$((start + ${range[1}))\n\nto find the affected lines, then drop \"warning:\" outside those lines.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
