    {
      "id": "489a24552284eb20a27e689de8d5fcf765b21087",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2022-04-02 00:56:09.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1\n\nSorry to backtrack on my previous request, but Oleg made a valid point that it is possible to cause errors in *other* parts of the script that are not within the context of the code being modified (e.g. removal of a variable or changing a function name).\n\nGiven that the patches to clean up all of the existing \"error\" cases in the test scripts have landed, it makes sense to report all \"error:\" cases anywhere in the modified script.\n\nI think it makes sense to keep the filtering code since we might consider in the future also printing \"warning\" messages within the scope of the modified lines, once we have a reasonable list of error types to keep/ignore:\n\nWarnings to ignore:\n warning: Declare and assign separately to avoid masking return values. [SC2155]\n warning: EXCEPT_SLOW appears unused. Verify use (or export if used externally). [SC2034]\n warning: mds1_FSTYPE is referenced but not assigned. [SC2154]\n warning: mds_HOST is referenced but not assigned (did you mean 'mds_host'?). [SC2154]\n\nWarnings to print:\n warning: This is a unicode quote. Delete and retype it (or quote to make literal). [SC1110]\n warning: Use \"${var:?}\" to ensure this never expands to / . [SC2115]\n\nbut there are many and I don't have an idea if it is easier to include or exclude warnings...  Something for another patch.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "7f63ace15f01d7638e7a06885b6d50da61295984",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 655,
        "name": "Arshad Hussain",
        "email": "arshad.hussain@aeoncomputing.com",
        "username": "arshad512"
      },
      "date": "2022-04-02 06:42:04.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\n>Sorry to backtrack on my previous request, but Oleg made a valid point that it is possible to cause >errors in *other* parts of the script that are not within the context of the code being modified (e.g. >removal of a variable or changing a function name).\n\nNo problem. :-)... and I agree.\n\n>Given that the patches to clean up all of the existing \"error\" cases in the test scripts have landed, >it makes sense to report all \"error:\" cases anywhere in the modified script.\n\nOK. Will make the necessary changes for this.\n\n>I think it makes sense to keep the filtering code since we might consider in the future also printing >\"warning\" messages within the scope of the modified lines, once we have a reasonable list of error >types to keep/ignore:\n\nOK. Will comment it for now, with a note of future work to be done.\n\n>Warnings to ignore:\n<snip>\n\n>Warnings to print:\n<snip>\n\n>but there are many and I don't have an idea if it is easier to include or exclude warnings...  >Something for >another patch.\n\nYes. Will handle this in other patch series. I have seen, that we can selectively exclude or include SC___ error codes. I agree they are pleanty and we could slowly build that list via \"SHELLCHECK_OPTS\".",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
